<p><b>Thomas Nagel</b> (born July 4, 1937) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher" class="mw-redirect">philosopher</a>, currently University Professor of <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">Philosophy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Law" title="Law">Law</a> at <a href="/wiki/New_York_University" title="New York University">New York University</a>, where he has taught since 1980. His main areas of philosophical interest are <a href="/wiki/Philosophy_of_mind" title="Philosophy of mind">philosophy of mind</a>, <a href="/wiki/Political_philosophy" title="Political philosophy">political philosophy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethics</a>. He is well-known for his critique of reductionist accounts of the mind in his essay "What Is it Like to Be a Bat?" (1974), and for his contributions to deontological and liberal moral and political theory in <i>The Possibility of Altruism</i> (1970) and subsequent writings.</p>
